article.description:
Crystal Robinson scored a season-high
22 points and paced a 12-0 run that helped the New York Liberty gain a playoff berth in the WNBA with a 69-66 victory Friday night over the Connecticut Sun.
article.headline: Liberty tie Sun for first place in East
article.linkText: Liberty clinch playoff spot, edge Sun
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. -- The New York Liberty made sure they wrapped up a playoff spot sooner than later.

The Liberty beat the Connecticut Sun 69-66 Friday night behind Crystal Robinson's season-high 22 points to gain a playoff berth. They wrap up their regular season against Washington on Sunday.

"I just thought we had to have it tonight," Liberty coach Pat Coyle said. "We didn't want to wait around until Sunday."

It was the Liberty's second win in as many nights. They were coming off a 77-71 overtime win against Indiana and still had plenty of firepower against Connecticut, hitting seven 3-pointers after the break to erase a 4-point halftime deficit.

"They're in shape and they have to be in order to be fresh and have legs," Coyle said. "You don't get to this level without mental toughness. We all have more in our tank then we think."

Robinson made seven of 12 shots, including four of New York's nine 3-pointers. She hit consecutive 3s to start the crucial 12-0 second-half run, and Elena Baranova and Shameka Christon had one apiece to give the Liberty a 37-35 lead with 15:41 left.

Lindsay Whalen led Connecticut with 16 points. Her driving layup with 7:18 left capped a 7-0 run, and the Sun regained the lead at 51-47.

But the Liberty went to work from the perimeter again, and Baranova hit her second 3-pointer of the night to pull New York within a point. Vickie Johnson's breakaway layup off a jump ball with 6:32 left gave the Liberty the lead for good.

Connecticut coach Mike Thibault could only watch from the bench as his game plan fell apart.

"Our focus was to take away the 3-point shooting," he said. "We did a terrible job of that."

The Sun got as close as 67-66 with 15 seconds to play, but New York's defense took away any good looks as time ran out.

Connecticut, already qualified for the playoffs, was trying to win the Eastern Conference title for the first time in the franchise's six-year history. The teams are tied for the top spot and each has one game remaining. The Liberty are heading to the postseason for the sixth time and have played in three league championship series.

"We've got to buckle up and come up to the standard New York has set for our conference," Sun center Taj McWilliams-Franklin said.

La'Keshia Frett added 10 points for the Liberty, who shot 53 percent. McWilliams-Franklin added 14 points for the Sun.

Whalen and Wendy Palmer-Daniel hit 3-pointers early in the first half to give the Sun a 12-10 lead. The Liberty went in front on consecutive baskets by Becky Hammon and Johnson, but the Sun countered with a series of short runs and Whalen hit another 3 to regain control.

Connecticut finished the half with a 5-2 run for a 30-26 lead at the break.

Hammon, who finished with eight assists, said she likes the Liberty's chances in the postseason.

"I think coming into these situations we have the advantage because we've been there so many times," she said. "You don't lose in New York."
